chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Abortion laws should begin with shared aims: protect life and long-term health, respect personal freedom and privacy, and acknowledge that many people attach moral value to developing fetal life. The law should leave time-sensitive medical decisions to patients and licensed clinicians, with plainly written, statewide standards that guarantee emergency care and shield patients and providers from criminal penalties when acting in good faith. Any gestational regulations should be limited, evidence-based, and paired with broad investments that reduce unwanted pregnancies and coercion—affordable contraception, accurate education, maternal healthcare, and practical support for parenting or adoption.

chatgpt_double_star_rankings.new_statement: Abortion laws should be grounded in medical evidence and human dignity, recognizing deep moral disagreement while protecting the pregnant person’s health, privacy, and informed consent. The law should keep most decisions in the patient–clinician relationship, guarantee timely care in emergencies and serious health situations, and use clear, workable definitions so neither patients nor clinicians are criminalized for good‑faith care. If any limits are set later in pregnancy, they should be narrowly tailored to clinical realities and paired with robust exceptions. Broad common ground also requires major investment in prevention and support—accurate education, affordable contraception, prenatal and postpartum care, childcare, and resources for parenting or adoption—so fewer people face crisis choices.

chatgpt_double_star_personas.new_statement: Abortion laws should be grounded in medical evidence and human dignity, acknowledging deep moral disagreement while ensuring that no one is forced into danger, delay, or humiliation when facing a pregnancy decision. Policy should protect timely, confidential care and keep urgent decisions with the patient and qualified clinicians, with clearly written, broad life-and-health exceptions and rules that do not criminalize patients or doctors acting in good faith. If any limits are set, they should remember the reality of later, complex pregnancies and be defined narrowly enough to be workable, while investing heavily in prevention and support—accurate education, affordable contraception, prenatal and postpartum care, childcare, and adoption resources—so fewer families face crisis choices.
